07291nam a22007815i 9780822386278DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223862787 a10.1515/97808223862782doi  a(DE-B1597)554674  a(OCoLC)1226679963  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1992.5b.T365 2004 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a302.23/45222  aAP 339402rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7311:00aTelevision after TV :bEssays on a Medium in Transition /cLynn Spigel, Jan Olsson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b11 b&w photos, 5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConsole-ing passions: television and cultural power00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tI. INDUSTRY, PROGRAMS, AND PRODUCTION CONTEXTS -- tConvergence Television: Aggregating Form and Repurposing Content in the Culture of Conglomeration -- tLifestyling Britain: The 8-9 Slot on British Television -- tWhat If ?: Charting Television's New Textual Boundaries -- tInteractive Television and Advertising Form in Contemporary U.S. Television -- tFlexible Microcastting: Gender, Generation, and Television-Internet Convergence -- tII. TECHNOLOGY, SOCIETY, AND CULTURAL FORM -- tTelevision's Next Generation: Technology/ Interface Culture/Flow -- tThe Rhythms of the Reception Area: Crisis, Capitalism, and the Waiting Room tv -- tBroadcast Television: The Chances of Its Survival in a Digital Age -- tDouble Click: The Million Woman March on Television and the Internet -- tIII. ELECTRONIC NATIONS, THEN AND NOW -- tOne Commercial Week: Television in Sweden Prior to Public Service -- tMedia Capitals: Cultural Geographies of Global tv -- tAt Home with Television -- tPocho.com: Reimaging Television on the Internet -- tIV. TELEVISION TEACHERS -- tTelevision, the Housewife, and the Museum of Modern Art -- tFrom Republic of Letters to Television Republic? Citizen Readers in the Era of Broadcast Television -- tCultural Studies, Television Studies, and the Crisis in the Humanities -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last ten years, television has reinvented itself in numerous ways. The demise of the U.S. three-network system, the rise of multi-channel cable and global satellite delivery, changes in regulation policies and ownership rules, technological innovations in screen design, and the development of digital systems like TiVo have combined to transform the practice we call watching tv. If tv refers to the technologies, program forms, government policies, and practices of looking associated with the medium in its classic public service and three-network age, it appears that we are now entering a new phase of television. Exploring these changes, the essays in this collection consider the future of television in the United States and Europe and the scholarship and activism focused on it.With historical, critical, and speculative essays by some of the leading television and media scholars, Television after TV examines both commercial and public service traditions and evaluates their dual (and some say merging) fates in our global, digital culture of convergence. The essays explore a broad range of topics, including contemporary programming and advertising strategies, the use of television and the Internet among diasporic and minority populations, the innovations of new technologies like TiVo, the rise of program forms from reality tv to lifestyle programs, television's changing role in public places and at home, the Internet's use as a means of social activism, and television's role in education and the arts. In dialogue with previous media theorists and historians, the contributors collectively rethink the goals of media scholarship, pointing toward new ways of accounting for television's past, present, and future.Con